{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8e972153052edb83", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== ABLATION (55934) ===\nAblation Study Table VII presents ablation results on the conversion model, using TokAN-1 (duration-free mode) as the base configuration. TABLE VII: Ablation study. All systems use TokAN-1 (duration-free mode). Best results in bold . System WER (% ↓ \\downarrow ) SECS ( ↑ \\uparrow ) Δ \\Delta PPG ( ↓ \\downarrow ) Source 15.81 — 0.5092 TokAN-1 9.23 0.3655 0.2533 w/o post-training 9.89 0.3791 0.2589 w/o fine-tuning 14.92 0.5605 0.4477 w/o pre-training 12.67 0.3894 0.2887 w/o CTC sup. 12.91 0.3846 0.2907 Effect of RL post-training. Removing the GRPO stage (“w/o post-training”) increases WER from 9.23% to 9.89% and Δ \\Delta PPG from 0.2533 to 0.2589. This confirms that task-level RL, directly optimized intelligibility and accent reduction, further improves the accent normalization performance. Meanwhile, SECS slightly increases without RL (0.3655 → \\to 0.3791), suggesting that RL’s accent-focused optimization mildly trades off speaker similarity. Effect of SFT (pre-training only). Removing the SFT stage (“w/o fine-tuning”) and relying solely on BART-style pre-training leads to substantial degradation: it works similar to direct resynthesis while being slightly worse. This confirms that BART pre-training alone is insufficient for accent conversion—fine-tuning on parallel token pairs is essential for learning the L2-to-L1 phonetic mapping. Effect of pre-training. Removing the BART pre-training stage (“w/o pre-training”) while retaining SFT increases WER from 9.89% to 12.67% and Δ \\Delta PPG from 0.2589 to 0.2887. This demonstrates that BART pre-training provides crucial language modeling priors over token distributions, enabling the model to better generalize during fine-tuning. Effect of CTC guidance. Further removing the CTC phoneme supervision from the encoder (“w/o CTC sup.”) increases WER to 12.91%, confirming the finding from [ 4 ] : explicit phonemic guidance is helpful for maintaining content fidelity during accent conversion. IX-F Token-Level Phonemic Distribution Analysis To evaluate pronunciation normalization at the token level, we analyze phoneme-specific token distributions using forced alignment [ 49 ] on the test set. We compute the KL divergence between the per-phoneme token distributions of converted speech and those of synthetic native targets. Figure 5 presents this analysis for Chinese-accented speech, before and after conversion with TokAN-1. Figure 5: Token-based phoneme divergence from native US English targets. Each cell shows the KL divergence between the token distribution of a given phoneme (row) in the analyzed speech and the native reference. Left: source Chinese-accented speech. Right: converted speech. After conversion, the diagonal becomes notably darker (lower KLD), indicating closer alignment with native pronunciations. Colored annotations highlight three prominent Mandarin-influenced mispronunciation patterns: dental-alveolar fricative confusion among /TH/, /S/, and /Z/ (red), devoicing of /JH/ to /CH/ (pink), and confusion between /N/ and /NG/ due to nasal coda weakening (orange). The post-conversion results show a significantly darker (lower-valued) diagonal, with the average on-diagonal KL divergence reduced from 1.076 to 0.519 (a 51.7% reduction), indicating successful transformation toward native-like pronunciations. Three prominent Mandarin-influenced English pronunciation patterns are highlighted: • Dental-alveolar fricative confusion (red): Mandarin lacks the English dental fricatives /TH/ and /DH/, c\n=== DATASETS / SETUP ===\nVIII-A Datasets LibriTTS-R [ 36 ] : High-quality native English speech dominated by the US accent. Used to select the configuration of the jointly trained SSL tokenizer and synthesizer. Emilia-EN [ 26 ] : Large-scale English speech dataset covering diverse speaking styles and accents. Used for BART pre-training and jointly training the SSL tokenizer and synthesizer. L2-LibriTTSR [ 5 ] : Synthesized non-native counterparts of LibriTTS-R utterances, covering multiple L2 accents. Used for SFT, together with LibriTTS-R. L2-ARCTIC [ 76 ] + ARCTIC [ 37 ] : Six non-native English accents (Arabic, Chinese, Hindi, Korean, Spanish, Vietnamese) with four speakers each; native US English speakers from ARCTIC. Used for SFT and evaluation. Native targets for L2-ARCTIC are synthesized using a zero-shot Matcha-TTS [ 50 ] trained on LibriTTS-R. We use the same 50/80 sentence split for validation/testing, consistent with [ 5 ] . GLOBE [ 70 ] : Multi-accent English speech corpus with diverse L1 and L2 speakers. Used for GRPO post-training. No paired native targets are required. VIII-B Compared Systems We evaluate TokAN against three baselines. FramAN (Frame-to-frame Accent Normalization) [ 6 ] : A three-stage frame-to-frame system. (i) A FastSpeech-like [ 61 ] non-autoregressive TTS model is trained on Emilia-EN, providing an accent-neutral text encoder and a flow-matching acoustic decoder; unlike [ 6 ] , we omit intermediate pitch/energy variables, which empirically degrade speech quality. (ii) A speech encoder distills Whisper-medium [ 58 ] features to match the text encoder output, with alignment from bournemouth-forced-aligner [ 60 ] and modality-matching loss on Emilia-EN. (iii) The speech encoder is fine-tuned on phoneme-aligned native targets synthesized by the TTS branch, combining modality-matching and flow-matching losses. FramAN always preserves the source rhythm, including the total duration. CosyAccent [ 5 ] : A direct non-autoregressive flow-matching model with a duration-ratio predictor. Before finetuning on the semi-synthesized data, we pretrain it with a stop-gradient operation on its encoder outputs. We evaluate two modes of CosyAccent: CosyAccent-1 (duration-free) and CosyAccent-2 (source-length). VEVO [ 73 ] : An autoregressive token-level conversion model that uses codebook size as an information bottleneck—a small-codebook HuBERT tokenizer for source content tokens and a large-codebook tokenizer for content-style tokens. VEVO mimics the style in an acce", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b79edf63-d735-41dc-887e-3dbbc02705cf", "uuid": "5afdb138-b6ad-4492-a77e-dbf4a044afbc", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T08:54:44.735Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== ABLATION (55934) ===\nAblation Study Table VII presents ablation results on the conversion model, using TokAN-1 (duration-free mode) as the base configuration. TABLE VII: Ablation study. All systems use TokAN-1 (duration-free mode). Best results in bold . System WER (% ↓ \\downarrow ) SECS ( ↑ \\uparrow ) Δ \\Delta PPG ( ↓ \\downarrow ) Source 15.81 — 0.5092 TokAN-1 9.23 0.3655 0.2533 w/o post-training 9.89 0.3791 0.2589 w/o fine-tuning 14.92 0.5605 0.4477 w/o pre-training 12.67 0.3894 0.2887 w/o CTC sup. 12.91 0.3846 0.2907 Effect of RL post-training. Removing the GRPO stage (“w/o post-training”) increases WER from 9.23% to 9.89% and Δ \\Delta PPG from 0.2533 to 0.2589. This confirms that task-level RL, directly optimized intelligibility and accent reduction, further improves the accent normalization performance. Meanwhile, SECS slightly increases without RL (0.3655 → \\to 0.3791), suggesting that RL’s accent-focused optimization mildly trades off speaker similarity. Effect of SFT (pre-training only). Removing the SFT stage (“w/o fine-tuning”) and relying solely on BART-style pre-training leads to substantial degradation: it works similar to direct resynthesis while being slightly worse. This confirms that BART pre-training alone is insufficient for accent conversion—fine-tuning on parallel token pairs is essential for learning the L2-to-L1 phonetic mapping. Effect of pre-training. Removing the BART pre-training stage (“w/o pre-training”) while retaining SFT increases WER from 9.89% to 12.67% and Δ \\Delta PPG from 0.2589 to 0.2887. This demonstrates that BART pre-training provides crucial language modeling priors over token distributions, enabling the model to better generalize during fine-tuning. Effect of CTC guidance. Further removing the CTC phoneme supervision from the encoder (“w/o CTC sup.”) increases WER to 12.91%, confirming the finding from [ 4 ] : explicit phonemic guidance is helpful for maintaining content fidelity during accent conversion. IX-F Token-Level Phonemic Distribution Analysis To evaluate pronunciation normalization at the token level, we analyze phoneme-specific token distributions using forced alignment [ 49 ] on the test set. We compute the KL divergence between the per-phoneme token distributions of converted speech and those of synthetic native targets. Figure 5 presents this analysis for Chinese-accented speech, before and after conversion with TokAN-1. Figure 5: Token-based phoneme divergence from native US English targets. Each cell shows the KL divergence between the token distribution of a given phoneme (row) in the analyzed speech and the native reference. Left: source Chinese-accented speech. Right: converted speech. After conversion, the diagonal becomes notably darker (lower KLD), indicating closer alignment with native pronunciations. Colored annotations highlight three prominent Mandarin-influenced mispronunciation patterns: dental-alveolar fricative confusion among /TH/, /S/, and /Z/ (red), devoicing of /JH/ to /CH/ (pink), and confusion between /N/ and /NG/ due to nasal coda weakening (orange). The post-conversion results show a significantly darker (lower-valued) diagonal, with the average on-diagonal KL divergence reduced from 1.076 to 0.519 (a 51.7% reduction), indicating successful transformation toward native-like pronunciations. Three prominent Mandarin-influenced English pronunciation patterns are highlighted: • Dental-alveolar fricative confusion (red): Mandarin lacks the English dental fricatives /TH/ and /DH/, c\n=== DATASETS / SETUP ===\nVIII-A Datasets LibriTTS-R [ 36 ] : High-quality native English speech dominated by the US accent. Used to select the configuration of the jointly trained SSL tokenizer and synthesizer. Emilia-EN [ 26 ] : Large-scale English speech dataset covering diverse speaking styles and accents. Used for BART pre-training and jointly training the SSL tokenizer and synthesizer. L2-LibriTTSR [ 5 ] : Synthesized non-native counterparts of LibriTTS-R utterances, covering multiple L2 accents. Used for SFT, together with LibriTTS-R. L2-ARCTIC [ 76 ] + ARCTIC [ 37 ] : Six non-native English accents (Arabic, Chinese, Hindi, Korean, Spanish, Vietnamese) with four speakers each; native US English speakers from ARCTIC. Used for SFT and evaluation. Native targets for L2-ARCTIC are synthesized using a zero-shot Matcha-TTS [ 50 ] trained on LibriTTS-R. We use the same 50/80 sentence split for validation/testing, consistent with [ 5 ] . GLOBE [ 70 ] : Multi-accent English speech corpus with diverse L1 and L2 speakers. Used for GRPO post-training. No paired native targets are required. VIII-B Compared Systems We evaluate TokAN against three baselines. FramAN (Frame-to-frame Accent Normalization) [ 6 ] : A three-stage frame-to-frame system. (i) A FastSpeech-like [ 61 ] non-autoregressive TTS model is trained on Emilia-EN, providing an accent-neutral text encoder and a flow-matching acoustic decoder; unlike [ 6 ] , we omit intermediate pitch/energy variables, which empirically degrade speech quality. (ii) A speech encoder distills Whisper-medium [ 58 ] features to match the text encoder output, with alignment from bournemouth-forced-aligner [ 60 ] and modality-matching loss on Emilia-EN. (iii) The speech encoder is fine-tuned on phoneme-aligned native targets synthesized by the TTS branch, combining modality-matching and flow-matching losses. FramAN always preserves the source rhythm, including the total duration. CosyAccent [ 5 ] : A direct non-autoregressive flow-matching model with a duration-ratio predictor. Before finetuning on the semi-synthesized data, we pretrain it with a stop-gradient operation on its encoder outputs. We evaluate two modes of CosyAccent: CosyAccent-1 (duration-free) and CosyAccent-2 (source-length). VEVO [ 73 ] : An autoregressive token-level conversion model that uses codebook size as an information bottleneck—a small-codebook HuBERT tokenizer for source content tokens and a large-codebook tokenizer for content-style tokens. VEVO mimics the style in an acce", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
