{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-81db47a7c66c1e65", "type": "tool_result", "content": "X Conclusion References License: CC BY 4.0 arXiv:2607.03928v1 [cs.SD] 04 Jul 2026 TokAN: Accent Normalization Using Self-Supervised Speech Tokens Qibing Bai, Shuai Wang, Yuhan Du, Bohan Li, Yannan Wang, and Haizhou Li (Corresponding authors: Shuai Wang and Haizhou Li.) Q. Bai is with the School of Data Science (SDS), The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen (CUHKSZ), China, and with Tencent Ethereal Audio Lab, Tencent, Shenzhen, China.S. Wang is with the School of Intelligence Science and Technology, Nanjing University, Suzhou, China, and with Shenzhen Loop Area Institute, Shenzhen, China.Y. Du is with the School of Intelligence Science and Technology, Nanjing University, Suzhou, China.B. Li is with the X-LANCE Lab, School of Computer Science, Shanghai Jiao Tong University, Shanghai, China.H. Li is with School of Artificial Intelligence (SAI), CUHKSZ, China, with Shenzhen Research Institute of Big Data, China, and with Shenzhen Loop Area Institute, China.Y. Wang is with Tencent Ethereal Audio Lab, Tencent, China.Samples: https://p1ping.github.io/TokAN-Samples .Code: https://github.com/P1ping/TokAN . Abstract Accent normalization (AN) seeks to convert non-native (L2) accented speech into standard (L1) speech while preserving speaker identity. The current techniques either require naturally recorded parallel L1–L2 speech for training, or suffer from quality degradation when supervised by synthesized targets. In this paper, we present TokAN , a token-based accent normalization framework that operates on self-supervised discrete speech tokens extracted from a L1–L2 jointly trained vector-quantization (VQ) tokenizer, without the need of synthetic supervisory speech. An autoregressive encoder-decoder model performs token-to-token conversion, translating L2-accented token\n=== TOKENIZER SELECTION ===\nTokenizer Selection Study We conduct a systematic study to identify the optimal tokenizer configuration. The selection criterion is the word error rate (WER) computed by a native-only ASR model on speech reconstructed from discrete tokens—a proxy for the tokenizer’s joint content preservation and reconstruction capability. Additionally, we consider the initial accent normalization ability, i.e., the extent to which the reconstructed speech has reduced accentedness even before any conversion, which we estimate by the same native-only WER metric on L2-accented speech reconstructed through the tokenizer. We focus on the accent-removing speech reconstruction capability and, therefore, use the source token durations instead of predicting them. IV-D 1 SSL Model and Layer We compare three SSL backbones at two commonly used layers: • Wav2vec 2.0 2 2 2 https://huggingface.co/facebook/wav2vec2-large-lv60 [ 3 ] : layers 17 and 22. • HuBERT-large 3 3 3 https://huggingface.co/facebook/hubert-large-ll60k [ 28 ] : layers 17 (used in the preliminary conference version [ 4 ] ) and 22. • WavLM-Large 4 4 4 https://huggingface.co/microsoft/wavlm-large [ 8 ] : layers 17 and 22. • W2V-BERT 2.0 5 5 5 https://huggingface.co/facebook/w2v-bert-2.0 [ 11 ] : layers 17 and 22. All configurations use a codebook of size 1024 and are trained on LibriTTS-R [ 36 ] . Table I reports the reconstruction WER on the L2-ARCTIC validation set. We adopt a native-only ASR model 6 6 6 https://huggingface.co/facebook/s2t-medium-librispeech-asr , simulating listener’s perception of L2-accented speech. This can be considered an intelligibility metric reflecting both content preservation and nativeness. TABLE I: Tokenizer Selection: SSL Model and Layer (Codebook Size = 1024, Trained on LibriTTS-R). WER (%) computed by native-only ASR. SSL Model Layer WER (%) ↓ \\downarrow Overall L2 Accents Source - 19.81 22.50 Wav2vec 2.0 17 22.33 25.24 22 87.88 90.08 HuBERT 17 21.29 24.02 22 18.97 21.46 WavLM 17 18.71 21.16 22 17.45 19.82 W2V-BERT 2.0 17 21.55 24.42 22 22.76 25.89 WavLM-Large at layer 22 achieves the lowest reconstruction WER, confirming its stronger phonetic encoding and accent robustness [ 8 ] . We fix the SSL backbone to WavLM-Large layer 22 for all subsequent experiments. TABLE II: Tokenizer Selection: Codebook Size (WavLM-Large, Layer 22). WER (%) by native-only ASR. Codebook Size WER (%) ↓ \\downarrow Overall L2 Accents 256 18.02 20.35 512 17.95 20.28 1024 17.45 19.82 2048 17.64 19.95 4096 18.27 2", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b79edf63-d735-41dc-887e-3dbbc02705cf", "uuid": "12e442f6-1866-44b4-ba37-ef660d53d3e2", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T08:55:54.473Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "X Conclusion References License: CC BY 4.0 arXiv:2607.03928v1 [cs.SD] 04 Jul 2026 TokAN: Accent Normalization Using Self-Supervised Speech Tokens Qibing Bai, Shuai Wang, Yuhan Du, Bohan Li, Yannan Wang, and Haizhou Li (Corresponding authors: Shuai Wang and Haizhou Li.) Q. Bai is with the School of Data Science (SDS), The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen (CUHKSZ), China, and with Tencent Ethereal Audio Lab, Tencent, Shenzhen, China.S. Wang is with the School of Intelligence Science and Technology, Nanjing University, Suzhou, China, and with Shenzhen Loop Area Institute, Shenzhen, China.Y. Du is with the School of Intelligence Science and Technology, Nanjing University, Suzhou, China.B. Li is with the X-LANCE Lab, School of Computer Science, Shanghai Jiao Tong University, Shanghai, China.H. Li is with School of Artificial Intelligence (SAI), CUHKSZ, China, with Shenzhen Research Institute of Big Data, China, and with Shenzhen Loop Area Institute, China.Y. Wang is with Tencent Ethereal Audio Lab, Tencent, China.Samples: https://p1ping.github.io/TokAN-Samples .Code: https://github.com/P1ping/TokAN . Abstract Accent normalization (AN) seeks to convert non-native (L2) accented speech into standard (L1) speech while preserving speaker identity. The current techniques either require naturally recorded parallel L1–L2 speech for training, or suffer from quality degradation when supervised by synthesized targets. In this paper, we present TokAN , a token-based accent normalization framework that operates on self-supervised discrete speech tokens extracted from a L1–L2 jointly trained vector-quantization (VQ) tokenizer, without the need of synthetic supervisory speech. An autoregressive encoder-decoder model performs token-to-token conversion, translating L2-accented token\n=== TOKENIZER SELECTION ===\nTokenizer Selection Study We conduct a systematic study to identify the optimal tokenizer configuration. The selection criterion is the word error rate (WER) computed by a native-only ASR model on speech reconstructed from discrete tokens—a proxy for the tokenizer’s joint content preservation and reconstruction capability. Additionally, we consider the initial accent normalization ability, i.e., the extent to which the reconstructed speech has reduced accentedness even before any conversion, which we estimate by the same native-only WER metric on L2-accented speech reconstructed through the tokenizer. We focus on the accent-removing speech reconstruction capability and, therefore, use the source token durations instead of predicting them. IV-D 1 SSL Model and Layer We compare three SSL backbones at two commonly used layers: • Wav2vec 2.0 2 2 2 https://huggingface.co/facebook/wav2vec2-large-lv60 [ 3 ] : layers 17 and 22. • HuBERT-large 3 3 3 https://huggingface.co/facebook/hubert-large-ll60k [ 28 ] : layers 17 (used in the preliminary conference version [ 4 ] ) and 22. • WavLM-Large 4 4 4 https://huggingface.co/microsoft/wavlm-large [ 8 ] : layers 17 and 22. • W2V-BERT 2.0 5 5 5 https://huggingface.co/facebook/w2v-bert-2.0 [ 11 ] : layers 17 and 22. All configurations use a codebook of size 1024 and are trained on LibriTTS-R [ 36 ] . Table I reports the reconstruction WER on the L2-ARCTIC validation set. We adopt a native-only ASR model 6 6 6 https://huggingface.co/facebook/s2t-medium-librispeech-asr , simulating listener’s perception of L2-accented speech. This can be considered an intelligibility metric reflecting both content preservation and nativeness. TABLE I: Tokenizer Selection: SSL Model and Layer (Codebook Size = 1024, Trained on LibriTTS-R). WER (%) computed by native-only ASR. SSL Model Layer WER (%) ↓ \\downarrow Overall L2 Accents Source - 19.81 22.50 Wav2vec 2.0 17 22.33 25.24 22 87.88 90.08 HuBERT 17 21.29 24.02 22 18.97 21.46 WavLM 17 18.71 21.16 22 17.45 19.82 W2V-BERT 2.0 17 21.55 24.42 22 22.76 25.89 WavLM-Large at layer 22 achieves the lowest reconstruction WER, confirming its stronger phonetic encoding and accent robustness [ 8 ] . We fix the SSL backbone to WavLM-Large layer 22 for all subsequent experiments. TABLE II: Tokenizer Selection: Codebook Size (WavLM-Large, Layer 22). WER (%) by native-only ASR. Codebook Size WER (%) ↓ \\downarrow Overall L2 Accents 256 18.02 20.35 512 17.95 20.28 1024 17.45 19.82 2048 17.64 19.95 4096 18.27 2", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
